commitResults.messageTitle: Standardise language for DG use cases
commitResults.messageBody: Previous fix missed a few necessary standardisations made here.

The feedbackToUser is passed to the resultDisplay UI, but the
application closes too quickly for the feedback to be rendered to the
user.

Let's add a 3 second delay upon exit.

Running the delay (and handleExit behaviour) on a separate concurrent
thread allows the feedbackToUser to be rendered by FXML.

The duration of the delay (3 seconds) is arbitrarily selected, and can
be modified later based on user feedback.

Let's disable the commandBox.

Disabling the commandBox prevents new commands from being executed. As
the handleExit behaviour is running concurrently with the application's
command execution, a command's behaviour might be interrupted before it
completes all its steps. For example, after exiting, the user deletes a
person record, but the application closes before the deletion is saved
by the storage module.

The commandBox is disabled in the concurrent thread. This allows some
time after an exit command when another command could be runned
illegally.

Let's move the disabling of commandBox out of the concurrent thread into
the main thread.

Disabling the commandBox in the main thread ensures that the commandBox
is disabled before the current command finish processing, in turn
disabled before another command can start processing.

commitResults.messageBody:
Application displays an internal error message instead of a
user-oriented message.

Let's restore it to the user-oriented message.

Assign command randomly assigns participants from the current displayed
list to the input study groups. The command takes in a minimum of one
study group as input.

If only one study group is provided, the assign command will assign all
currently displayed person to the study group. Otherwise, each person is
assigned to one of the input study groups at random.

Study group names only accept alphanumeric characters.

Let's also accept dashes "-" to increase the expressiveness of study
group tags.
